04509nam a22006975i 9780813543925DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20072007nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135439257 a10.36019/97808135439252doi  a(DE-B1597)530119  a(OCoLC)1058097022  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aLB2376.3.C6bL5 2008eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a370.116/22221 aLi, Hongshan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aU.S.- China Educational Exchange :bState, Society, and Intercultural Relations, 1905-1950 /cHongshan Li. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2007] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Educational Exchange and the Visible Hand -- t1 Emerging as Facilitator -- t2 Tearing Down the Barriers -- t3 Qinghua: The First Joint Experiment -- t4 From Central Administration to Party Control -- t5 Maintaining the Educational Front -- t6 From Expansion to Termination -- t7 A Historical Perspective -- tEpilogue: Restoring Educational Relations with the Visible Hand -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aU.S.-China relations became increasingly important and complex in the twentieth century. While economic, political, and military interactions all grew over time, the most dramatic expansion took place in educational exchange, turning it into the strongest tie between the two nations. By the end of the 1940s, tens of thousands of Chinese and American students and scholars had crisscrossed the Pacific, leaving indelible marks on both societies. Although all exchange programs were terminated during the cold war, the two nations reemerged as top partners within a decade after the reestablishment of diplomatic relations. Approaching U.S.-China relations from a unique and usually overlooked perspective, Hongshan Li reveals that both the drastic expansion and complete termination of educational ties between the two nations in the first half of the twentieth century were largely the results of direct and deep intervention from the American and Chinese governments. Benefiting from government support and collaboration, educational exchange succeeded in diffusing knowledge and improving mutual understanding between the two peoples across the divide of civilizations. However, the visible hand of government also proved to be most destructive to the development of healthy intercultural relations when educational interactions were treated merely as an instrument for crisis management.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aEducational exchangesxChina. 0aEducational exchangesxUnited States. 0aEducational exchangeszChina. 0aEducational exchangeszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813543925423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813543925.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK